This contraption displays four tumblers with a series of sequential numbers on each. It appears you can move them by hand.

Entry 1. 
I am the former wizard and lorekeeper of clan Turgbin. As long as I can remember I have always possessed a fascination with numbers, figures, and equations. My study of the secret mysteries of numbers, coupled with a skill in necromancy, showed me things to drive a mortal mad. Over time however I realized that those that plotted against me were many. Thus I retreated deeper into my work, not able to comprehend my genius I am feared by my community. My experiments in granting life to the unliving through magical
Numerology were the stuff of whispered legends, in hushed voices I could hear them talking about me. On the verge of a break through one night I threw off past constraints and took unwilling specimens for my research. I Broggle slew a dozen of my fellow clan members and dragged their bodies back to this isolated burrow before the Turgbin clan was roused. They ignorantly raised a mob, and encountered me amidst my bloody task, covered in glyphs and numbers of power. I can only imagine their thoughts of impotence as the furniture in my lair, also engraved with magical glyphs and numbers shifted eerily about. I just glared out at them in defiance, the whimpering and hissing, corpses of my kinsmen piled
around me. The weaklings didn't dare enter my burrow to retrieve their fallen; they were terrified of what further attacks I might make if provoked. So, under the direction of Clanmaster Dagrin Bunner Riddlemaker Turgbin, an old and foolish bard, the gnomes sealed me up in this burrow. Clanmaster Dagrin feared my power as a wizard and knew that I would be able to get free, so he crafted a devious magical ward to entrap me here. 

Entry 2.
How dare my clansmen betray all that I have done for them? Today they imprison me in my cave but only yesterday they praise me for my genius. They are ants, and as ants can not possibly hope to understand my work. I view the lives that I took as a needed sacrifice. How else could I explore the limits of my discovery?! No matter. I shall now set upon the work of unlocking my prison so that I may once more pursue the limitless boundaries of Arcane Numerology. The lock is some form of mathematical puzzle. Can they be so small as to think the great and terrible Broggle would not balance any equation?

Entry 3. 
This puzzle is maddening. How could they possibly perceive an algorithm so complex? I must solve this puzzle soon or else my supplies will run out. However I vow to not eat any of my victims as they will be needed in further experiments. 

Entry 4. 
I have decide on another course of action. My former clan must have hired a rival mathematician in order to create such a impressive equation. I need more time to solve it and thus have decided to bond myself with the corpses of my past victims in order to preserve my consciousness. My arcane numerology should make this more than possible to create a flesh golem that retains my psyche. 

Entry 5.
My work is finished. I have sewn the body parts together for the host creature. I have devised a simple device that will fuse us together and have laid the unholy numbers upon the inactive golem. Tomorrow I will complete the process. This has been a wonderful experiment and once I am free of this cave I must later reflect on further modifications possible to the machine I have built.

Entry 6.
Success! I am now worthy and capable to finish my research. In time I shall free myself and then torture each of my kinsmen in turn. I shall paint endless equations with their blood. Time is now on my side.   

*You notice the last few journal entry appears in a larger more hurried script*

Entry 7.
For posterity's sake I shall try and keep a true account here of my life's crowning achievements. I was led here by chance, or was it? I must consider this further at a later time. Only to realize there was another student, no teacher of numerology. I am not sure of his whereabouts or fate but I have used his work to amplify my own research in thaumaturgy. There are many experiments left undone. The results of which must be examined at length. 

Entry 8.
Dr. Broggle was so close but missing a key element. He bonded himself with the creature. While genius in it's own right it failed in that the form he chose was a destructible one. He should have realized as I that the blood of a creature carries its memories. I will instead bond my life force with his machine and then be able to create a static host not easily destroyed. From there I can seed the world with my children. I must hurry though. My disease eats at me. I feel that I am loosing myself. I yearn to be back with my love. It has been so long since our last visit. I find myself spending more and more time in this cave. The villagers are starting to ask questions in Tobaro. They blame disappearances on me above and beyond those of my students. At least this cave seems to block out my dreaded nightmares.

Entry 9.
This is the last record of Doctor Albrecht Villikommf's failing human form. I have had a breakthrough today. In building upon the work of the genius Broggle I have discovered how to perfect his devices. By merging my very mass and tissue into the (creature producing device) I can bind my eternal soul within it far from the corruption of this mortal husk I currently wear. This will create a chain reaction that shall result in perpetual creation of more enhanced creatures. The (machine) will take upon it the characteristic of regeneration thereby bestowing upon me a type of eternal life as I meld my essence with the (machine). As long as it is provided with fresh tissue on a regular basis (My dearest love has promised to send me specimens from time to time.) we (yes I must get used to the thought of myself as part of this (machine) will not go dormant. In fact given long enough of an undisturbed period I could amass quite a large army of creatures.
The Diary of Broggle Maldor Quillkeeper Turgbin

What a strange series of events have brought me to this cave. 

For many years I have worked above and below ground as an accountant for some of the most devious citizens of the realm. Year after year I have helped them avoid taxation from the Duke. What can I say numbers are my talent. Unfortunately I experienced a wrinkle in my plan when I was exposed for what I am and was ushered to a dreary dingy cell. You can imagine my surprise when waiting for judgment the entire side of the building where I was being held shattered into bits and a large grey head poked in. Soon I was whisked up and placed in a sack only to be released into this cave. 

Turns out this giant stone man that took me is living here and he is some kind of elder or witchdoctor of his people.  While meditating here he stumbled upon a mathematical equation written on the back wall. Man, he is fixated on this. I have to say the number sequence is quite an interesting one.  Anyway, I guess this Giant, Drell is his name by the way, is in some kind of puberty that is normal for his kind but he does not seem to be able to transform until he figures this number out. So when some of the locals mentioned me and my talent with numbers he just up and grabbed me. Now he promises me that he will set me free if I can solve this for him. To tell the truth I am enjoying working on the problem. It is such a curious sequence.


        Y
      63

    F
    +119


     x21

  BU  I D
  -42?10

      I
      ?7

        Y
      63

     B D
     -10

   WH
    =5x9


      x6

        I
       ?


       ?

One thing that is becoming apparent to me is that this is equation has has nothing to do with numbers.

Value.value: This area is a short, wide room with a stale smell to it. Two large sets of bookshelves reach up to the ceiling. There are four roundish doors opposite the way you came in., two to the right and two to the left. They are all engraved with symbols.Between them is some sort of contraption on the wall. This chamber has all the looks of an opulent, but ancient, gnomish burrow. The walls, floor, ceilings, and furniture are all engraved with strange sigils that appear to move and shift at the corners of your eyes, but seem solid and unmoving when viewed closely. The wall behind you is the only unmarked area of the room. It is a flat stone, set into the wall, engraved with the same math puzzle seen outside.

The hallway opens into a once-opulent gnomish bedchamber. Uncounted ages have taken their toll, and now even the enourmous bed is little more than a heap of tattered brown rags. Curiously, this room is very cold.
This door opens to a long hall that slopes downward and continues for several paces. The walls, floor, and ceiling are alive with the crawling glyphs..

The hallway immediately led to a gnome sized kitchen. Although spacious and well stocked, it is clear that no one has disturbed this room for generations. Inscrutable glyphs cover the walls and ceilings of this room.

This hallway opens into a large space where odds and ends are irregularly stacked in crates and boxes. There are no other exits from here. The glyphs that crawl over the walls are present in this chamber as well.
